 Production (wasting very little while working or producing something) of Chinese farm-related: (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from (away from cities) 
 household survey data 
 Jirong Wang *,Gail L. Cramer, Eric J. Wailes 
 Department of Farming-based Money flow and (away from cities) (the study of people), University of Arkansas, 221 Farming Building, Fayetteville AR, 72701, USA 
 Accepted 10 May 1996 
 
 Abstract 
 A shadow-price profit edge of something/unexplored area model is developed to examine production (wasting very little while working or producing something) of Chinese (away from cities) families in farming operations. 
 The model includes price distortions resulting from (not totally pure/not totally correct) market conditions and (how money affects people's lives) and institutional restrictions, but 
 keeps/holds the advantages of (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area properties. The shadow prices are received/made from through a generalized profit function guess. The 
 shadow-price profit edge of something/unexplored area is then guessed and an (wasting very little while working or producing something) index based on the guessed profit edge of something/unexplored area is figured out/calculated and rotten to 
 household (features/ qualities/ traits). Scientific results using data from China's (away from cities) Household Survey for 1991 reject the neoclassical profit 
 (biggest increase/best possible extent) guess based on market prices in favor of the general model with price distortions. Farmers' useful thing/valuable supply gift and 
 education influence their response to the market restrictions, this way change  their performance in terms of (wasting very little while working or producing something). The guessed (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 index ranges from 6% to 93% with a sample average of 62%. Families' educational level, family size and per person net income are 
 positively related to production (wasting very little while working or producing something). Families living in mountain areas or with family members employed by the government or 
 state businesses are (compared to other things) inefficient. Reducing market helping action, allowing right of use of farm land to be moved (from one place to another) among 
 families, encouraging traveling of excess farm labor, and (helping increase/showing in a good way) farmers' education will improve (away from cities) families' (wasting very little while working or producing something) in 
 farming-based production. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 The (wasting very little while working or producing something) gains from improving useful thing/valuable supply 
 portion resulting from money-based changes in 
 China's farming have been dramatic. Fan ( 1991) 
 guessed that about 63% of the working well change 
 (at an average of 2.13% per year, 1965-1985) is 
 (named after/discovered by/caused by) improvement in (wasting very little while working or producing something). Lin ( 1992) 
 found that the working well change resulting from 
 different changes made up 42.23% of the output growth 
 during 1978-1984, and no increasing (popular thing/general way things are going) in (related to computers and science) change was detected. Central to this change towards free markets in Chinese agricul- 
 
 ' Corresponding au_pair thor. 
 
 ture is the behavior of the individual (away from cities) household. 
 With the (away from cities) Household Responsibility System 
 (RHRS) the basic production unit was moved/changed from 
 collectivized farms to the (away from cities) families. Other 
 changes allowed for the sale of valuable things to private parties and the free flow of extra (away from cities) labor 
 to local businesses and city-based  areas. The farming-based 
 part/area responded to these changes with increased 
 production for most major valuable things due to working well gains. With the full (putting into) use of 
 RHRS nationwide in 1983-1984, the question of 
 whether production (wasting very little while working or producing something) is still a great (possibility of/possible happening of)  working well growth remains unanswered. 
 Although the money-based changes have greatly reduced 
 direct control by government over production, different interferences in farming-based markets still distort 
 
