 farmers' production decisions. The relationships between (wasting very little while working or producing something) and market indicators and household (features/ qualities/ traits) have not been well studied in 
 this unfolding process of farming-based reform. A better understanding of these relationships should aid 
 policymakers in creating improved (wasting very little while working or producing something)-improving policies and in judging the effectiveness of past 
 changes. These relationships are also of interest to 
 policymakers in other nations where government 
 plays a big part in traditional farming. 
 Production (wasting very little while working or producing something) is usually carefully studied by separately examining its two parts/pieces: technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). Recent developments reported in the books combine both measures into one system. This approach enables more 
 (producing a lot with very little waste) guesses to be gotten by (at the same time) 
 guessing the system (e.g. Kumbhakar, 1989; Kalirajan, 1990). However, previous research (after- 1978) 
 on Chinese farming-based working well focused on total 
 factor working well, while technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and 
 allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) were rarely examined 1- 
 Although (random/including random data points) production edge of something/unexplored area functions 
 are most commonly used in studying production 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something), Yotopoulos and others argued that a production function approach may not be appropriate 
 when guessing the production (wasting very little while working or producing something) of individual farms because they may face different prices and 
 have different factor gifts (Ali and Flinn, 
 1989). An attempt to incorporate firm level prices 
 and input use led to (make money/get something good) function creation. The 
 early development of profit function models did not 
 provide a number-based measure of firm clearly stated/particular (wasting very little while working or producing something) (Aigner et al., 1977). Ali and Flinn (1989) 
 directly guessed farm-clearly stated/particular (wasting very little while working or producing something) from a 
 random coefficient profit edge of something/unexplored area function using 
 market prices. In general, the use of standard dual 
 representations of the production structure needs/demands 
 the similar maintained guesses of cost 
 minimization or profit (biggest increase/best possible extent), subject to parametric market prices. So, in the case of controlled 
 businesses or (not totally pure/not totally correct) markets, as in China, these 
 guesses may be invalid. 
 A generalized profit function (behavioral (money made/good thing received) 
