 function) approach which incorporates market distortions resulting from (not totally pure/not totally correct) market conditions has 
 been developed in the books. Kumbhakar and 
 Bhattacharyya (1992) developed a behavioral profit 
 function to test the appropriateness of a neoclassical 
 profit function and the effect of education and farm 
 size on allocative performance. Their model, however, does not provide a number-based measure of profit 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) for each farm. A more recent study done by Ali et al. (1994) employed both (random/including random data points) 
 edge of something/unexplored area and behavioral (money made/good thing received) functions separately in 
 a study of Pakistan farming. The rejection of 
 profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) based on watched/followed market prices 
 from the behavioral profit function, however, points to/shows that their (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area function, which 
 was specified by using watched/followed market prices, is 
 subject to misspecification. (related to/looking at/thinking about) after- 1978 
 Chinese farming-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) studies, very few employed the dual approach and none incorporated 
 market distortions. 
 The goal of this study is to carefully study production (wasting very little while working or producing something) of farm families facing different 
 market restrictions in Chinese farming. An guess process that incorporates market distortions but 
 keeps/holds the advantages of (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area properties in (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis is developed in this study. 
 China's (away from cities) Household Survey data for 1991 are 
 used for the scientific analysis. First&#126; a behavioral 
 profit function is used to get farmers' shadow 
 prices. Then a (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area profit function, 
 using the shadow prices received/got from the behavioral profit function, is guessed and the (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 index is received/made from and related to farm families' 
 information about people to identify the factors that 
 affect farm families' (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 
