 3. Data and scientific guess 
 The data used for this scientific application are a 
 subsample of China's National (away from cities) Household Sur- 
 
 21 
 
 vey for 1991. This survey, started in 1955 by the 
 General Organization of (away from cities) Socio-Money-based Survey of the State (related to studying numbers) Bureau (SSB), changed 
 from the Chinese (away from cities) Household Expense Survey started in the late 1970s. Since 1984, a multistage sampling procedure combined with period of time (or space) 
 sampling at the lowest level has been used in the 
 survey design to secure/make sure of the random nature of the 
 sample and to (make small) sampling errors (State (related to studying numbers) Bureau of China, 1993). The survey records 
 all major production and consumption activities of 
 70 000 participating families during the survey 
 year. 
 Farmers' production activities were influenced by 
 different market distortions which mainly came from 
 government helping action. By I991, for example, the 
 state contract (instance of buying something for money) for a specified amount of 
 output at a price fixed below the market price and 
 the purchase of amounts that went beyond the contract amounts under the (what people commonly call a/not really a) 'negotiated 
 prices', which in most cases were also lower than 
 market prices, were major government influences in 
 farming-based output markets. In the farming-based input 
 markets, government-owned businesses delivered 
 farm inputs, such as chemical (material that makes plants grow better)s and diesel 
 fuel, at low fixed prices to producers for many years. 
 To help purchase, the government has often 
 used input payments to cause cooperation from 
 farmers 8 . 
 Other sociopolitical and institutional restrictions 
 faced by Chinese farmers also cause market distortions. For instance, there are always shortages in 
 major material input supplies such as (material that makes plants grow better). Some 
 farmers may be able to get an (good) enough supply of 
 (material that makes plants grow better) at the state distribution prices because of 
 their personal relationship with state (services businesses/government units), while 
 others may have to pay a 'shortage premium'. Village leaders andjor families with non-farm-workers 
 may have special privileges, such as access to credit 
 or receive cash payment for their sales to the state 
 
 8 Since 1993, China has brought changes to its input supply 
 system. Now, a wide variety of businesses owned together 
 and by the government are delivering inputs to (away from cities) area (US 
 Department of Farming, 1993). However, the state planning 
 system still forces (numbers-based) restrictions on farmers' access to 
 paid-for inputs (You  and Rozelle, 1994). 
 
 22 
 
