 5. Summary and policy effects/results/suggestions 
 This study uses a profit function approach which 
 combines technical and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the 
 profit relationship to carefully study farm families' production (wasting very little while working or producing something) in China. To deal with the/to speak to the  existence 
 of different market distortions in Chinese farming, 
 we adopt a idea  of shadow-price profit edge of something/unexplored area in 
 this study. Measurement and rotting of the 
 families' production (wasting very little while working or producing something) are received/got by 
 guessing the shadow profit edge of something/unexplored area function, which 
 incorporates price distortions resulting from (not totally pure/not totally correct) markets, (how money affects people's lives) and institutional restrictions. Scientific results using 1991 China's (away from cities) 
 Household Survey data point to/show that a profit-making the most of farm's decision on outputs and inputs is 
 based on their shadow prices rather than watched/followed 
 
 market prices. It is also found that there is a significant difference/different version in production (wasting very little while working or producing something) among farm 
 families in China. Guessed production (wasting very little while working or producing something), measured by the profit (wasting very little while working or producing something) index, range 
 from 6% to 93%, with 11.8% percent of the farm 
 families' (wasting very little while working or producing something) levels being lower than 50%. 
 The mean of the profit (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 62%, which is 
 close to the 69% for the coastal area and the 48% 
 for the central area found in Wu (1995) using 
 1985-1991 (related to a local area) data. These results suggest a 
 great scope for improvement in production (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 The profit (wasting very little while working or producing something) is significantly explained by 
 the production-related (features/ qualities/ traits) and farm management practices. Especially, farmers' education, 
 farm size and per person net income are important 
 (numbers that change/things that change) to raise profit (wasting very little while working or producing something). The factors affecting (money made/good thing received) (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) negatively are small family 
 size (less than three people) and low per person net 
 income. Families living in mountain areas and 
 families with family members employed in the 
 government or state businesses are profit inefficient. 
 Given the existing government of input and output 
 prices in China's farming, one end/end result that can 
 be drawn from this study is that produces of price 
 distortions must be thought about/believed in farm behavior studies. This model has completely/in a hinting way (made a part of you) these distortions through the shadow prices. Rejection of the 
 market price model points to/shows that opportunity costs 
 of useful things/valuable supplies are not reflected by the watched/followed market 
 prices when there are binding external restrictions 
 and allocative inefficiency. So, scientific studies 
 that use (money made/good thing received) (cost) function with watched/followed market 
 prices as the opportunity costs of useful things/valuable supplies may give 
 inappropriate results. 
 The second end/end result drawn from the study is 
 that a great (possible power or ability within/possibility of)  (wasting very little while working or producing something) gain can be gotten by reducing market distortions in China's 
 farming. The (away from cities) Household Responsibility System, as the first phase of the (away from cities) money-based changes 
 that focused on the production operating (machine/method/way), 
 has (in a big way) improved farm families' (wasting very little while working or producing something). Although (away from cities) input and output market changes have been done since 1985, different 
 market restrictions still remain effective in preventing farm families' best useful thing/valuable supply portion. 
 The a big differences between the market prices 
 and farmer's opportunity costs, found in this study, 
 
 J. Wang et al.j Farming-based Money flow 15 (1996) 17-28 
 
 hints that farm families' allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 
 influenced by the market distortions. 
 The study also finds (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of 
 scale exist in China's household farming system. 
 Both technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 are positively related to operational size, which is 
 also partly figured out by/decided by family size and per person 
 net income. 
 The above findings have important policy effects/results/suggestions. All previous studies show/tell about that a big 
 improvement in China's farming-based production (wasting very little while working or producing something) has happened from the institutional changes 
 made from 1978 to 1984. With the full (putting into) use of the household responsibility system nationwide in 1983-1984, slow growth in crop production 
 and working well has shifted the focus of farming-based 
 development towards technical change. This study 
 points to/shows that big working well gains can be 
 received/got by continuously improving farm families' production (wasting very little while working or producing something). Both technical and a)locative (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) can be improved by eliminating 
 market distortions that mess up the function of price 
 signal and cause allocative inefficiency. Especially, 
 removing the government's monopsonistic power and 
 (related to managing and running a company or organization) forces on major farming-based product 
 purchase and (instance of buying something for money) of quota responsibilities in the 
 output market should allow market prices to reflect 
 the opportunity costs of the products. In the input 
 market, (helping increase/showing in a good way) the supply of not enough material 
 inputs, such as chemical (material that makes plants grow better) and fuel, rather 
 than restricting and price payments, could eliminate 
 the 'shortage premium' paid by some farmers and 
 over-use of the inputs by others. A more liberalized 
 market enables production ((money made/good thing received)) to return to its 
 edge of something/unexplored area from the interior and shifts the edge of something/unexplored area upward. The reason for this shift is that the (possible power or ability within/possibility of) 
 the money-based changes and modem technologies appears to be underestimated because the best practice 
 farms, which are basis for guessing the (possible greatness or power), 
 would probably also be held back by (how money affects people's lives) and institutional factors. 
 The study also hints that potential (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 gain can be (accomplished or gained) by increasing a household's 
 operating scale. Especially, allowing a (compared to other things) 
 (when there's not nearly enough of an important or valuable thing), land, to be moved (from one place to another) to families 
 with a high labor /land ratio should increase the 
 production (wasting very little while working or producing something) of these crop farms. As a result, improved useful thing/valuable supply use needs/demands development 
 
 27 
 
 of a land rental market or a well-conducted land use 
 right move (from one place to another) (machine/method/way) as a complement to the 
 land contract system 17 - The market can pick winners 
 and losers and set apart land to those who can use 
 it (in a way that produces a lot with very little waste). 
 Clearly, a farm household's production (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 is affected by its management practices and the 
 farm's production-related (features/ qualities/ traits), which in 
 tum are influenced by (how money affects people's lives) conditions. For 
 instance, a farmer's management ability is influenced by school availability and cost of education. It 
 is this way important for China's farming-based development to have an institutional (surrounding conditions) that helps the farmers' (how easy something is to get to, use, or understand) to education, and 
 provides a (how money affects people's lives) (surrounding conditions) that encourages market exchange in land and labor. 
 
